%N A394851 Decimal expansion of the unique solution x > 0 to Sum_{k>=1} arcsin(1/k^x) = Pi.
%C A394851 arcsin(z) = Sum_{j>=0} (j+1) * binomial(2*j+2, j+1) * z^(2*j+1) / ((2*j+1)^2 * 2^(2*j+1)).
%C A394851 The convergence of this series is slow, (j+1)*binomial(2*j+2, j+1) / ((2*j+1)^2 * 2^(2*j+1)) ~ 1/(2*sqrt(Pi)*j^(3/2)).
%C A394851 Since zeta(j) ~ 1 + 1/2^j + 1/3^j + ..., convergence can be accelerated if we divide the series into two parts (depending on the required accuracy) and from a certain j0 we consider zeta(j) ~ 1 for j > j0.
%C A394851 Mathematica can express Sum_{j>=j0} (j+1)*binomial(2*j+2, j+1) / ((2*j+1)^2 * 2^(2*j+1)) explicitly using hypergeometric functions.
%e A394851 1.51328357044357571880830360227346441557369810543368067872657178752830479...
%t A394851 digits = 108; j0 = Floor[digits*Log[10]/(3*Log[2])] + 1; rest = FullSimplify[ Sum[((j + 1)* Binomial[2*j + 2, j + 1])/((2*j + 1)^2*2^(2*j + 1)), {j, j0, Infinity}]]; RealDigits[ x /. FindRoot[ Sum[(((j + 1)*Binomial[2*j + 2, j + 1])/((2*j + 1)^2*2^(2*j + 1)))* Zeta[(2*j + 1)*x], {j, 0, j0 - 1}] + rest == Pi, {x, 3/2}, WorkingPrecision -> 108]][[1]]
